remarks: Our netting operations and past history of this lake, indicate that it is lacking in bluegills and bass. At one time the lake was named Bluegill Lake. Mr. Dinkert, and some people who have camped here for a number of years, say there hasn't been a bluegill taken for the past nine years. I would like to recommend 2,000 yearling bluegills and 1,000 smallmouth mouth bass to be planted this fall.

point_of_examination: from the access on east side
area_covered: shoreline of north third of lake and south tip
remarks: Recommend continuing the no size and no limit fishery on LMB. Growth of LMB is at a virtual standstill. In fall of 1977, LMB averaged 8.2. They are thin and few have yet attained even 10 inches yet

point_of_examination: Random - a map of survey locations is in the file.
remarks: This & previous surveys show a dominant sublegal sized largemouth bass population coupled with a large black bullhead population. It is doubtful if any type of game fish could bring off a success year class in this situation until numbers of bass are reduced.

point_of_examination: 10 min area from inlet tube going north along east shore. 10 min. area along west shore southwest of island. 10 min. area along boat launch site.
area_covered: See point of examination - to depth of 4 ft.
remarks: The largemouth bass seem to be in good condition, but forage is lacking. Capturing of fish species was limited due to water clarity of approximately 10 inch depth. Also a heavy blue-green algae bloom heavy enough to cause a bad odor.

Shoreline cruise beginning at boat landing near outlet and proceeding counter-clockwise until terminating near the double-overhead door boathouse located on point directly across from boat landing.
remarks: This survey was done to check on the success of the walleye, muskellunge and largemouth bass introductions of 1967 and '68. Following the partial chemical treatment of August, 1967, the following introductions were made: (1) 1.5 million walleye fry planted 5/6/68, (2) 1500 Tiger muskellunge (x 7.2") planted 7/10/68, (3) and 2225 Fingerling LMB (x 2.3") planted 11/67. Only one floodlight on shocking craft was operating so collecting efficiency was down, but the sample obtained gives a good picture of the population structure in general. Approximately 12 additional muskys were turned over but not captured, plus innumerable walleyes. One 6.8" inch left pelvic clip LMB was taken, this being from the 1967 plant.

remarks: A 10 lb. sample of the bluegills seined contained 132 specimens. Avg. wt. 1.21 oz. Avg. size 4.9 in. Weather and water temperatures were not the best for seining. The need for a partial thinning with antimycin is evident for this lake. Some bluegills afflicted with some light blotchy areas with dark speckles were sent to Hnath at Wolf Lake. . point_of_examination: East side

point_of_examination: South side
remarks: The fishing pressure on the lake is very heavy. Large strings of bass and bluegills are taken. Perch and pike have become very scarce.

point_of_examination: Northeast side
remarks: Bluegills are especially abundant. Only a very small portion of those caught were kept. Bushels of bluegills could be caught along the shore of this lake. They far exceed in numbers of all the other fish.

entire lake

remarks: Bob Davey set 2 nets by himself. Although they were set tight and straight (quite a job with one hand!), they were fished very poorly. Many aquatic weeds on ropes and anchors after 1 night set. Selective treatment program evaluation. Enough were observed to indicate needing another partial. Additional comments on back Comments: con't. 1970 - Bluegills stunting - growth indexes negative by more than 1" for all ages sampled. 1974 - One year after 1st antimycin partial. All age classes checked equal or exceed state avg. growth rates. 1978 - 3 years after last antimycin partial. Growth indexes range from -0.1 to +0.5", not as good as 1974 but still far better than in 1970.

remarks: Purpose of survey was to check present fish population and in particular to check northern pike abundance. Comments from residents and our catch results indicate pike numbers are way down. Several residents were surprised at the small size of the blue bluegills in our catch. They said what they caught (con't on back) were larger. I've fished this lake and I agree with them. Northern Pike if planted in small sizes may not fare well in presence of reported mud pickerel population. Recommend no further management of this lake at this time.

Minnows observed on shoal. Shore seining indicated abundance of Iowa darters, numerous black nosed dace and perch fingerlings (1960)

remarks: samples from several points on lake needed; 7 seine hauls taken; bass & perch in all samples, darters in sample on NE shore, E point & W point (large), bluntnose in from of camp & off large W point. Collection preserved.

point_of_examination: SW cove, NW cove and NE shore of lake
South Shore, North Shore and Northeast Shore.
remarks: This lake is very acid and looks like poor fish habitat. No fish take in Exp. Gill Nets. Extreme high water levels at this time.

Near boat well on east end, south and west shoal
remarks: Turtles numerous, some clams and tadpoles observed

point_of_examination: Parallel to north shore through / or in deep hole
Off north central portion of lake
remarks: Turtles had chewed on most of fish in net. Bullheads reported but none taken. Walleyes rumored but doubt if they would survive under conditions found (shallow, warm, easily roiled water).

point_of_examination: NW section
remarks: Fish chewed on by turtles. Neascus noted on one northern pike. Two fishermen in lake.

point_of_examination: SE section
Shore seining along north, east and west shoals
remarks: Observed 2 adult N. Pike in weeds near outlet

point_of_examination: Off point NE by north
remarks: 2 N. Pike, 3 W. suckers. Large bullheads reported by fishermen

point_of_examination: West shoal off state campground. East shoal near inlet from Bodi Lake
remarks: Clams abundant on west shoal, large schools of minnows observed on west, north and east shoal. Also minnow fry showing up. Steep drop off from South SE portion of lake. Painted turtle observed.

point_of_examination: Off mouth of creek SSE steep drop off
West shoal; NE point and east shoal (4 rep. samples)
remarks: Clams abundant on west shoal. Large schools of minnow and some perch and sunfish observed on most of shoal area. Moreso so on north and west.

point_of_examination: off creek from south side of lake
remarks: Fishermen getting a few pike and some small perch ( (one 6# pike taken yesterday)

point_of_examination: West Basin - NW center
remarks: Thomas Brown and another party who have cabin on Buckeye Lake witnessed net lift.

point_of_examination: SW corner of lake
remarks: One beaver, 2 loons and 1 sea gull observed

point_of_examination: NE shoal
remarks: Reports received this summer that a number of brook trout 2-3 - 3 1/2" were caught from this lake. There is no record of it being stocked by the Conservation Dept.

point_of_examination: Eastern bay - off cottage Sta. 1
area_covered: East bay - south and east shore

point_of_examination: Net set #1 - Eastern bay - off cottage Sta. 1
Central west shore
remarks: A common sense seine was used along a portion of the shoreline, and a number of unidentified minnows were preserved. They included young suckers, and golden shiners, probably. A dead mud minnow (U. limi) was picked up on the beach. Sunfish fry were also taken by seining.

point_of_examination: (1) Across north basin (2) across SW basin (sinkhole)
remarks: Bottom is marl overlaid with pulpy peat, almost pure marl at bottom of sinkhole; only 2 golden shiners in net No. 2

point_of_examination: 4 exp. gill nets set from shore; one each mid-south shore, mid-east shore, mid-north and mid-west shore.
remarks: Survey done to verify need to treat. All fish taken were recorded on length frequency sheet and disposed. Pumpkinseed sunfish are abundant and splake are in poor condition. To be treated 5/13/77

point_of_examination: 150 yds. of campsite
area_covered: Between 2 points out 150 yds. from campsite
remarks: Fishing success has been poor according to fisherman camped here for 3 weeks.

point_of_examination: South end of fingerlake bay
remarks: No sign of bass; water too dark for observation of shoal. Campground on north end used recently.

point_of_examination: North shoal near campground
remarks: Heavy growth of grasses due to low water last year makes shoal seining difficult. Observations nil due to dark color of water.

point_of_examination: Mouth of western dogleg - net set #1
Northeast end
remarks: Turtles worked over fish (painted turtles observed). Intermittent outlet obstructed by old (50 years or more) beaver dam. 12" red pine and dense leatherleaf growing on it. Water level now above normal - adequate spawning ground for northern pike.

point_of_examination: North shore Adj. to P.A.S.
depth_of_collection: 1' foot to 3' feet (Fyke); 1' foot to 6' feet (Trap)
remarks: Heavy electrical activity during night may explain the very small sample. If this class had had more time, these nets would have been left out one more night.

point_of_examination: Fishing site
remarks: Abundance of minnows & fingerling sunfish, rock bass, LM Bass observed along shoal, too soft for wading. Crayfish abundant.

point_of_examination: SW corner of east portion
remarks: Some neascus in perch (rel. clean), neascus in rock bass flesh (some clean), neascus in pumpkinseed seeds sunfish, largemouth bass clean. Brook trout not planted here by Fish Division (probably introduced by local resident).

point_of_examination: North side of SW portion
remarks: Water in lake above normal. Both white and yellow water lillies present. Shore seining indicates both large and smallmouth bass reproduction 1960 - more largemouth, also Iowa darters and blacknosed dace, numerous perch fingerlings and some 1960 pumpkinseed. seed

point_of_examination: 11 to and 40' from north east shore of west arm of lake
Parallel to and 40' from north east shore of west arm of lake.
30' east of inlet and 30' from shore set perpendicular
perpendicular to NE shore of east end of lake. 150' north of outlet - 100' from shore

set across mouth entering west arm of lake

Sand bar across mouth separating two basins
SE corner (14) NE corner (14) North (10) SW corner (24)
remarks: Water normal, 2 mergansers on lake. Condition factor very good. Trout ripe. Some with both pelvis fins clipped; few fish with left pectoral (intermediate size class). Gill lice.

point_of_examination: 35' east off sand bar which separates the two major basins of the lake and set perpendicular
SE shoal and SW shoal
remarks: Observed 25 to 30 trout schooled on SE shoal in a sand overlain with organic. Some trout had gill lice. Condition factor very good, especially of female fish. Assisted by Carl Westman, Newberry.

point_of_examination: 75' feet off SE shore of bay on west end of lake
Hook and line - In lagoon at west end of lake and off the east shore of lagoon
Across middle from south shoal
remarks: Few trout taken opening weekend; reports of no fish rest of summer (this lake is usually a good producer). Water level about 6" below normal. Less lilies along south shore than usual; more along NW shoal. Cranberry crop good this year; black cherries ripe. Road & landing to lake shows signs of considerable use this summer. On hand at time of lift: CO Raycunich, FO Walsh & C. Westman 500' net rest.

point_of_examination: Middle of south shore running north.
Mid center and east end
remarks: Deep water set - no fish - bottom plants decayed where before were abundance. Shallow water set - good; fish taken at about 10' depth. 4 - 5 loons spent summer on lake.

point_of_examination: Along northwest, east and southeast shores plus Burnt, Greenfield and Gull Island
remarks: These fish were collected incidental the 1979 walleye egg take. A total of 6230 walleye were handled: 4932 [less than] 38.0 cm. (15.0") and 1298 > than] 38.0 cm. (15.0") which were tugged and released. There were 102 recaptured with 1978 tags.

point_of_examination: Across Center
remarks: Numerous salamanders, tapeworms found in fish, no gill lice, made stomach analyses. Fish in very good shape.

point_of_examination: South shore: Hoffenberger's, Rioux's Points and Emerey's Resort plus Burnt Island and Birch Point
remarks: This collection is a summary of the walleye spawn collection

point_of_examination: Off west end of Burndt Island
remarks: No visitors present. Conferred with Mr. Strough, manager of Red Owl store in Curtis regarding our netting operation. All fish returned to lake. Strough reports numerous large walleyes brought in for freezing; perch fishing reported v. good.

point_of_examination: Off point 350 yards west of Manakiki Lodge
remarks: No visitors (Manistique L. Resort Association, resorters & Cons. officers notified). All fish returned to lake.

point_of_examination: Off southeast side of Long Point
remarks: Sid Foster, Newberry, assisted as recorder. Reported operation to Mr. Straugh. Red Owl - Curtis; R. Brawley, Mackinac Co. Rd. Com. & Doyle Short, guide (latter reports 1955 a v.g. good year for WE fishing on Big Manistique. Could always get some fish; its know how that produces results.

point_of_examination: Off point near Manistique Lake Lodge; 1/4 mile north of fishing site.
remarks: Anderson who has resort adjacent to P.F. F. site report fishing very good this summer by angler that know how to fish the various species present. No visitors.

point_of_examination: Off Hoffie's Point, half mile north of Public Fishing Site
remarks: Hole in bottom of trap (muskrat) some fish possibly lost. Sid Foster, Newberry assisted as recorder. Lake very rough at this point.

point_of_examination: Off point half mile NW of Cedar Springs Resort
remarks: Sid Foster, Newberry assisted as recorder. One unknown observer from shore. Lake very rough - shipped water a number of times.

One mile from south shore, northwest of Cedar Springs Resort.

point_of_examination: Northwest shore
remarks: One haul made, all fish collected were preserved.

Portage Creek - outlet

point_of_examination: Northeast of Cedar Springs Resort - just off dropoff off

remarks: Abundance of small perch around net. Sucker s being given to local residents for smoking and fertilizer.

point_of_examination: North shoal at mouth of small creek east of Tressler's Resort
remarks: Spawning just off mouth of small spring creek. 75% female, 25% male.

point_of_examination: Northwest shoal, off Roat's Park
remarks: Moved net from Roat's to Tressler's

point_of_examination: North shoal, front of Tressler's Resort
remarks: Some ciscoes (8 - (8-10") Y. Perch & minnows feeding on sucker eggs

Northwest shoal - off Roat's Park

point_of_examination: Tresslers west creek
remarks: Suckers marshaling in large numbers off mouth of creek

point_of_examination: West shoal, front of Novak's Shoreline Resort
remarks: Number of shiners and darters spawning in same area

North shoal, directly front Tressler's Rustic Resort
North shoal, 100 yards west of Tressler's east Creek
North shoal, 200' E of Tressler's east creek

remarks: Abundance of small perch on shoal.

point_of_examination: North shoal directly in front of Tressler's Rustic Resort
remarks: Abundance of small perch on shoal, obs. one small rainbow. All fish cleaned up from last week. Suckers held in Tressler's boats with water flowing from well on them.

point_of_examination: Off Birch Whispers Resort (Byer) middle east shore
remarks: Assisted by J. Novak and D. Wiskin. K. Tressler and 10 or 12 other people present. Water rough

point_of_examination: off Wildmere Resort (Wiskins) NE shore
remarks: Assisted by J. Novak & D. Wiskin, K. Tressler & 10 other persons present. Water very rough.

point_of_examination: Off Shoreline Resort (Novak's) west shore
remarks: Assisted by J. Novak & D. Wiskin, J. Lamoreaux; Schaeffer's and 10 or 12 tourists on hand.

point_of_examination: Off Phil's Rustic Bar (S. Central shore)
remarks: Assisted by J. Novak & D. Wiskin; about 10 or 12 other people on hand.

point_of_examination: Off Phils Bar (South central shore)
remarks: Assisted by J. Novak & D. Wiskin; about 12 other people on had to witness lift.

point_of_examination: Off R. Fyvie's (N Central shore)
remarks: Assisted by J. Novak & Don Wiskin; Bud Schaefer & Father & two other people witnessed lift.

point_of_examination: Off Honkonen's cottage east central shore west of brush shelters
remarks: Assisted by J. Novak & D. Wiskin; Mr. Gabbard, resort op. witness.

point_of_examination: Off tip of sand bar from NW portion of lake in line from Schaefer's to Phil's Bar
remarks: D. Wiskin & J. Novak assisted in lift; witnessed by Schaefers & tourist at Novak's. Catch displayed to Welters, Phils, McCauley (Twp. Supvr.), Gabbard, Talcott & Byers & Flowers. Dead fish turned over to Newberry State Hospital (97#)

point_of_examination: East side of sand bar extending SE from NW portion of lake 1/2 mile from shore.
remarks: Assisted by J. Novak & D. Wiskin; Bud Schaeffer & father on hand to witness lift.

point_of_examination: 1000 yards west of east center
remarks: Very windy - fish discarded (Cusino bear food)

point_of_examination: 500 yards northwest of Luce County Park
remarks: Very windy during daylight - fish discarded

point_of_examination: Various points around lake; both shallow and deep; on shoal and near center.
remarks: Assisted ably by resort operators J. Novak and D. Wiskin. Water pretty rough most of time for good observation. Interest mostly with few resort operators.

point_of_examination: Bathing beach, south shore, directly in front of small pier and stand.
remarks: Three hauls made. Small minnows (3/4") numerous but because of the number of snags only a few were taken.

point_of_examination: Northwest shore
remarks: 2 nets tied together, 10 small perch, 1 small walleye preserved, no scales were taken from these. 1 mullet preserved but scales were taken from it.

point_of_examination: West shore at small inlet from farmhouse
area_covered: 10 by 10 ft. in each of two hauls
remarks: Two hauls made. These are the only large minnows found on this lake up to date but note Q 57

point_of_examination: County Park Bathing Beach - 50 yards west
remarks: Minnows numerous, seining hard due to large amount of debris, sticks, logs. All fish collected were preserved.

point_of_examination: Directly in front of county park, south side of lake.
remarks: All fish collected were preserved. Seining difficult due to large numbers of snags. Minnows not very abundant.

point_of_examination: 800 feet opposite Luce County Park
remarks: All fish preserved, scales taken also

point_of_examination: Extreme south end and NE point
remarks: The deep set took no fish at all; 5 taken in shallow set were found in 5 - 5-10' depth (shoal water). All fish were females. CF only fair, probably due to closeness to spawning season. Very little food in stomachs. Flesh pink; exterior dark to grey silver, pink spots indistinct. A few gill lice found. No sign of spawning activity on shoals. The fish were not as fat as during the summer months, The flesh was still quite edible and as yet had not acquired the "spawning time flavor."

point_of_examination: SE shoal and NW shoal
remarks: 2 rainbow taken in SE corner at 10 ft. depth. Condition factor very good; only unidentified gunk in stomachs. Fishing light. Access good. Cabin on north shore improved & brush cut. Water above normal.

point_of_examination: Off Beaver Lodge SW shoal; south of island
remarks: 4 LM Bass fingerling (3") observed along north shoal. No forage minnows observed along entire shoal.

point_of_examination: Eastern and Middle "pockets"
remarks: Took nothing in nets, fish taken by slow trolling with spinner and worms; fish starting to rise toward evening. Lake and surroundings give evidence of some play this summer. Fish in good shape; pink meat.

point_of_examination: Across narrows in east portion.
remarks: Perch started showing up in creel last year for first time since poisoning. Fresh otter sign observed.

point_of_examination: East end across entire lake
remarks: No LM Bass; abundance Y. Perch. Obs. nothing on boat trip around entire lake. Some fresh beaver activity. Obs. 1 great blue heron. Lightning struck large W. Pine on N. shore - severing it half way down. Scales - weight/length. Data taken on 3/Y. Y. Perch. Perch eating perch. 22 females; 9 males. One to 7 in 7-8.5" class. 8-15 class, 8 - 15 in 5.5-6.5" - 6.5" class. (Males 5.5-6.0" - 6.0" mature, row well developed).

point_of_examination: Near outlet - east of island
remarks: Lake about a foot high at this time. Lake has been open in this area for three weeks.

point_of_examination: Directly in front of Price's Resort
remarks: Approximately 900 Small-mouth Bass thrown back (counted those of one seine haul and estimated the rest). All the rest preserved.

point_of_examination: West central portion just north of McGregor - Kane cabins.
remarks: Abundance of small N. Pike caught 1955; also obs. during winter 1954-55. Some good SM fishing reported 1954-55; perch fishing tapering off some; rock bass prominent in catch (small size)

point_of_examination: East bay
Channel to Cranberry Lake and shore 100 feet on each side of channel.
area_covered: About a dozen hauls - 10 ft. by 10 ft.
remarks: No fish taken, on shore wind and great amount of debris, seining difficult.

point_of_examination: Directly in front of 1 first camp campground (Deer Park)
remarks: All fish caught preserved. Seining difficult because of large amount of rubbish. Minnows were not found. Took 4 smallmouth mouth bass.

point_of_examination: Long narrow bay, on north side of lake, south of Dr. Defuitt's cabin. 3 hauls on west side of bay.
remarks: All fish caught were preserved. Insects, snails.

point_of_examination: Directly in front of Cicottes Cabin
remarks: 80 Small-mouth Bass returned to lake, a fair sample kept - all the rest of the fish caught were preserved.

point_of_examination: West shore for a distance of 500 feet
area_covered: Between 20 and 30 hauls - all short except with 25' foot seine - 25' feet by 25' feet
remarks: Few fish caught were preserved. Many fish present but seining difficult.

point_of_examination: Opposite long narrow bay, in center of lake.
remarks: Scales taken from only 8 of 16 perch - and 2 of 13 suckers, rest of suckers and perch same size. 12 hour set.

point_of_examination: Directly off point on north shore (west of camp ground) about 300 yards off shore
remarks: All fish collected were scaled etc. Very few game fish, many suckers

West (20) center (15) East (10)
remarks: Condition factor very good. Male fish well colored. Most fish taken on shoal water - none in deeper stratas. Possible poaching - numerous fish can be observed from shoal; about 50 hooded mergansers on lake also few blacks and teal. Water mod. high.

point_of_examination: East portion of west basin
remarks: Check for presence and CF of trout - growth rate of Bluegills - no trout observed rising either day - bluegills feeding heavily on surface.

point_of_examination: Northern end of lake
East shoal
remarks: Water level slightly above normal. Seining difficult due to abundance of grass, weeds and debris on shoal. Leeches common. Painted turtles observed.

point_of_examination: Net set #1 - Southeast shore - off cabin and dock
1 net in each of 3 main basins
NE portion main basin 150 yds from shore
remarks: Three fishermen watched lift. Perch fishing reported poor this fall compared to last year.

point_of_examination: North end of Finger Bay
remarks: Minnows observed. Few N. Pike have neascus (black spot). Condition factor of white suckers very good. Fish observed jumping seem to be Small mouth Bass.

point_of_examination: North Shoal - East end of Forestry Camp Ground
remarks: Two fishermen observed lift. Fish observed jumping by campers and fishermen, 12# N. Pike caught 9/10/62 by camper. Number of small N. Pike caught past two years; Rainbow catch almost nil last two years.

point_of_examination: Northeast corner - opposite flooded pothole.
remarks: Cysts in perch liver, few neascus in skin of perch. Fishermen report taking some nice bluegills. One rainbow reported caught lately.

point_of_examination: Directly in front of C.C.C. Camp beach
area_covered: 2 hauls with 100 ft. seine - 100' feet by 150'. feet. 2 hauls 10' feet seine - 10' feet by 10' feet

point_of_examination: Directly opposite C.C.C. Camp Dock
remarks: All fish collected were used for data.

point_of_examination: South - southwest side - east of inlet
remarks: Some neascus in skin of pike. Pike had perch in stomach, condition factor of fish very good.

point_of_examination: 1/4 mile southwest of C.C.C. Camp Dock
remarks: No minnows taken. All fish collected were preserved.

point_of_examination: 100 yds. east of State Forest Service dock on NW part of lake. Set perpendicular to shore

point_of_examination: East portion

point_of_examination: Off point on East shore; of SW point; in NW bay

West side

point_of_examination: Off point on E shore; off SW point.
remarks: Only two nets were set because numerous recently planted yearling brook trout were observed. All but 3 of trout collected were from 1969 yearling plant. Stomachs of most trout checked contained Sticklebacks and 1 small trout also contained caddis larvae.

point_of_examination: Southwest bay, west shore, from south shore NE across SE bay.
remarks: Observed prolific number of minnows. Netted 5 very large and healthy brook trout. They were caught in about 8 - 10 feet of water, minnows in stomachs.

point_of_examination: 100 feet east of outlet on west end of lake. Net set from weed beds into lake.
remarks: This end of lake is full of submerged plants. Beaver dam about 100 yards away on stream that leaves lake. Most bullheads found in this net - all about 6 inches. Water color very reddish brown.

point_of_examination: Along north shore of lake
remarks: Shore goes out gradually for about 15 feet then drops sharply to about 7 feet. Lake is eroding on north shore.

point_of_examination: Northwest shore into lake 300 yards from outlet.

point_of_examination: Off NE and SW shores
remarks: No fish taken, but summer chemistry indicates water suitable for most species. May have fair potential for brook trout, but winter chemistry should be checked before making any plantings.

point_of_examination: Off SW shore
remarks: First plant of brook trout made on 6/2/69 at ave. length of 4.9". inches. Ave. length of 19 brk. trout collected during this survey was 8.5", inches, for an average increase of 3.6" inches in less than 2 months. Stomach samples indicate smaller trout feeding on dragonfly larvae, larger trout feeding on brook sticklebacks.

point_of_examination: West half of lake - a number of sets along the shoreline of the lake.

remarks: Good catches of walleye northern pike, smallmouth bass, and yellow perch. No small walleye taken perhaps reflecting the scarcity of suitable reproductive habitat.

point_of_examination: Toward S.E. corner of impoundment, 300' north of dam, from vegetation line on east shore outward.

Both sides of impoundment, at intervals along the shoreline to distance of 4 miles above am. Many types of habitats seined. By and large, bottom is soft, of clay and muck, apparently. Much vegetation.
remarks: A great abundance of crayfish--up to about 50 (small ones) per seine haul. N eine haul taken without some, Some minnows; many fingerlings. No habitat seen believed suitable for walleye young. Bottom mostly soft, water murky, vegetation with much clinging algal growth. Along east shore, about 1 1/2 to 2 miles N. of dam, seepage spring [?nters] lake--cold - cold water--10' - 10' wide where it enters lake. Here over 100 legal size rainbows were seen; 6 taken in the net had dorsal clipped. One seen in group (not netted) had a small lamprey attached. (These were probably planted on 8-5-47, , at Osborndale, out of Paris.)

remarks: This survey was conducted to evaluate the selective treatment program. Panfish growth remains above state average although fish in survey were smaller than in 1977.

point_of_examination: within 5 ft. contour
remarks: Some residents complained about small bluegills and perch. Lake is quite shallow with maximum depth around 10 feet. Predators seem to be lacking. Northern pike should be stocked and perhaps a partial thinning of the bluegills would be in order.

point_of_examination: entire lake
remarks: A few residents complained of small bluegills and perch. Lake is quite shallow but does not winterkill. Maximum depth is 10 to 12 ft. May require additional predator stocking.

point_of_examination: northwest end of lake
within 5 ft. contour of shoreline
remarks: Visibility was hampered due to plankton bloom; yellow perch were very small; fair bluegill population; good largemouth bass population.

point_of_examination: entire lake
remarks: Bluegills small 4 - 6". Had only 1 or 2 fish about 7". Crappies abundant, but generally small and thin. Survey done in conjunction with selective treatment program.

point_of_examination: Entire lake
remarks: Survey is in conjunction with Selective Treatment Program. Our survey results show a reduction of the average size for panfish from last year's data. Smaller fish are more abundant.

point_of_examination: Entire Lake
remarks: Survey is follow-up to selective treatment program. Bl Large Bluegills show growth improvements. . Large spawning white suckers were present on NW shoreline. . Bluegills fishing is excellent. .

point_of_examination: entire lake
remarks: Although relatively few panfish were collected, it appears that a stunted population condition may exist.

point_of_examination: inside 5 ft. contour
remarks: Small bluegills very abundant. Small largemouth bass lacking. A partial treatment on blue bluegills followed by a bass stocking would benefit the lake. Common shiners abundant.

point_of_examination: Off west shore, south half of lake.
remarks: All fish taken on files. There was a considerable mayfly hatch on the lake this evening. This started at 8:30 P.M. and the crappies were rising extensively for them. Mayflies apparently Hoxagenia

point_of_examination: nets were set off the northeast shore, off submerged island and in front of the public access site.
remarks: Good adult pike population; however, reproduction is limited for pike. Reset nets for perch; however, was unsuccessful. Scuba divers reported seeing numbers of small perch.

point_of_examination: Sets were made at selected locations to survey the entire lake.
gear_used_kind: 2 trap nets, 2 fyke nets, 2 exp. gill
remarks: Cottage owners complained of carp, but none were taken in nets. A nice size range of bluegills averaging over 6 inches was revealed. Looks like one of our better fishing lakes at this time. No management is recommended at this time.

point_of_examination: inside 5 ft. contour
remarks: Lake appears to be in good shape. Recommend no further management at this time. Two green sunfish (5.6 & 5.9) were also collected.

point_of_examination: Along the north and northeast shore, two net sets.

At 11 pm, 40 ciscoes removed, these scale sampled but not preserved, at 10 am took 31 ciscoes and 1 northern pike all scale sampled but not preserved.

point_of_examination: NA
remarks:
No natural reproduction of walleyes but survival and growth of stocked walleyes very good. Northern pike population seems to be down. Bluegills small but chunky. Not many fish collected in the survey. Recommend night electrofishing survey to complement the netting survey and also to better assess the largemouth bass population. Lake may be good prospect for stocking walleye fingerlings. See below for further remarks. Gillnets removed after one night. 
Mean growth index of all panfish and largemouth bass below state average. Growth of northern pike appears good. Mean growth index of Age V & VI walleyes is 1.6 inches above state average.

remarks: REMARKS: Special reference should be made concerning the numerous fish found dead washed upon the shore, apparently killed by a fungus. Specimens were sent packed in ice to the Institute for Fisheries Research in hope that the causative organism could be ascertained. On a measured shore line 246 feet in length 66 dead bluegills were found. In another area 100 yards in length 100 dead fish were also found. In addition to bluegills, a few scattered specimens of sucker sp.?, bullheads, and perch were also found. In all cases the more mature fish were affected, fingerlings and fry were apparently "immune". . The entire lake had no steep shore. Roads extended to almost any point around it.
